Countries such as Mauritius firstly found Omicron strain infection cases - Xinhuanet
Message from Beijing of the Xinhua News Agency on December 12, reported by foreign journalists of the Xinhua News Agency: Mauritius, Cyprus and Malawi firstly have reported to find the infection cases of Omicron strains, the novel coronavirus mutation recently.
Mauritius reported two infection cases of Omicron strains on December 10 for the first time.
According to introduction from Kelesh Jagutpal, minister of Ministry of Health of Mauritius, one of the infected person was a tourist departing from South Africa and arrived in Mauritius on November 27; the other infected person was a local inhabitant of Mauritius, who was detected as positive in nucleic acid testing on November 30 after contacting a person returning from South Africa.
The nucleic acid testing results of the two infected persons changed to negative after isolation and treatment in the hospital, and they have returned to their residence.
It was announced by Ministry of Health of Cyprus on December 10 that the country confirmed three cases of infection with the Omicron strains for the first time.
All of the 3 infected persons were students who came back from other countries for a travel at the beginning of this month; all of them were not hospitalized because they were mild cases.
In order to prevent the spreading of the Omicron strains, the government of Cyprus increasingly improved the prevention and control strength.
All the passengers above 12 years old who enter the country by plane shall accept nucleic acid testing at their own expenses in the airport from December 6 to the next January 10.
It was also announced by Ministry of Health of Cyprus on December 10 that they started vaccinating the Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine for children of 5 years old to 11 years old for the country.
Kunbizze Chiponda, minister of Ministry of Health of Malawi, said on December 9 that Malawi found 3 cases of infection with the Omicron strains for the first time.
The department of health of Malawi developed genomic sequencing for 12 COVID-19 positive samples collected from November 9 to December 2, and found the 3 cases of infection.